06981nam a22011415i 9783110338270DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20142014gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2013478872  a(OCoLC)897161614  a97831103382707 a10.1515/97831103382702doi  a(DE-B1597)214652  a(OCoLC)880458854  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aHV6275b.C667 2014eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a327.7305622300aConspiracy Theories in the United States and the Middle East :bA Comparative Approach /ced. by Michael Butter, Maurus Reinkowski. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (378 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 alinguae & litterae : Publications of the School of Language and Literature Freiburg Institute for Advanced Studies ,x1869-7054 ;v290 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConspiracy Theories in the United States and the Middle East is the first book to approach conspiracy theorizing from a decidedly comparative and interdisciplinary perspective. Whereas previous studies have engaged with conspiracy theories within national frameworks only, this collection of essays draws attention to the fact that conspiracist visions are transnational narratives that travel between and connect different cultures. It focuses on the United States and the Middle East because these two regions of the world are entangled in manifold ways and conspiracy theories are currently extremely prominent in both. The contributors to the volume are scholars of Middle Eastern Studies, Anthropology, History, Political Science, Cultural Studies, and American Studies, who approach the subject from a variety of different theories and methodologies. However, all of them share the fundamental assumption that conspiracy theories must not be dismissed out of hand or ridiculed. Usually wrong and frequently dangerous, they are nevertheless articulations of and distorted responses to needs and anxieties that must be taken seriously. Focusing on individual case studies and displaying a high sensitivity for local conditions and the cultural environment, the essays offer a nuanced image of the workings of conspiracy theories in the United States and the Middle East.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 4aVerschwörungstheorien. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aComparative analysis.  aConspiracy theories.  aMiddle East.  aTransnational narratives.  aUnited States of America.1 aButter, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButter, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChrist, Birte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Poli, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunst, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFathi, Schirin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFenster, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerbert, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerrmann, Sebastian M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerzog, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnsrud, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnight, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKenzie-McHarg, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNefes, Türkay Salim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb